US Steel has addressed its planned merger with Nippon Steel through a combination of litigation, regulatory extensions, and reaffirmation of its commitment, while the effect on business operations remains uncertain due to ongoing legal and regulatory hurdles. The all-cash merger at $55 per share was announced on December 18, 2023, and stockholder approval was obtained on April 12, 2024 (99% of votes cast). Non-U.S. regulatory approvals were received by May 30, 2024 from the EU, Mexico, Serbia, Slovakia, Turkey, and the UK. The merger was blocked by President Biden via executive order on January 3, 2025, prompting US Steel and Nippon Steel to file joint lawsuits on January 6, 2025. The deadline for closing was extended to June 18, 2025, by CFIUS on January 10, 2025. In its January 30, 2025 earnings release and 2024 10-K, US Steel reaffirmed its commitment to closing the transaction through legal action and the $55/share price. Investment commitments from Nippon Steel total at least $2.7 billion, including no less than $1 billion for Mon Valley Works and approximately $300 million for Gary Works, as detailed in the January 6, 2025 8‑K. No restructuring of the deal or a separate $1 billion investment at Gary Works has been confirmed in any SEC filing. A future-dated press release (December 22, 2025) on US Steel’s newsroom mentions a $350 million blast furnace reline at Gary Works backed by Nippon Steel, but this has not been published or filed with the SEC as of April 2025. On April 7, 2025, President Trump ordered a new CFIUS review of the deal. The impact on business operations remains pending resolution of the litigation and the new review.

